\begin_layout Itemize
In Clausious inequality, with half the process reversible, half irreversible,
 you're able to show that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int\frac{dq}{T}\le\Delta S
\]

\end_inset

then for a thermally isolated system, you say the lhs is zero and conclude
 that for such a system the entropy always increases.
 Now why wouldn't 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta S=\int\frac{dq_{r}}{T}
\]

\end_inset

 also = 0 if the system is thermally isolated? [in case you've forgotten,
 you had resolved this with Diksha] 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Comment: You had also using this, shown the equivalence (partly atleast)
 of the Careothedeory's statement of the first law.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Kardar's page 101, why does the first order change in entropy, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta S$
\end_inset

 have to be zero for a given first order reversible change of coordinates
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Is entropy really a state function even when 
\begin_inset Formula $\int dq/T$
\end_inset

 is done on an irreversible path? What happens stat mechanically?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How to map the 
\begin_inset Formula $\oint dq/T<0$
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta S>0$
\end_inset

 in stat mechanics?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
